Time Series Running Data¶

Objective¶

The objective of this assignment is to identify good models for classifying time series data.
The data is from an accelerometer sensor and there are samples of fatigued and non-fatigued running. The data has been segmented into strides and the segments (samples) are labelled F (fatigued) and NF (not fatigued). The data for two subjects A and B are available in the files fatigueA.csv and fatigueB.csv. This dataset is extracted from a much larger dataset described here.
At present, the best performing method for time-series classification is Rocket. A rocket implementation is available in the sktime tool kit. This sktime implementation can be used in this assignment.
Some code to get you started in available in the notebook RunningCore.

x = []
accuracies = []
accuracies_train = []
for i in np.arange(0.1, 1, 0.1):
    X_train_temp, X_test_temp, y_train_temp, y_test_temp = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=i, random_state=100)

    accuracies_train.append(accuracy_score(y_train_temp, y_sgd_pred_temp_train))
    x.append(i)

loss_list = ["hinge", "log_loss", "modified_huber", "squared_hinge", "perceptron", 
             "squared_error", "huber", "epsilon_insensitive", "squared_epsilon_insensitive"]
rocket_accuracies = []
rocket_accuracies_on_training = []
rocket_cv_scores = []

for i in loss_list:
    sgd_log_classifier = SGDClassifier(loss=i, random_state=100)
    sgd_log_classifier.fit(X3d_train_transformed, y_train)
    y_sgd_pred = sgd_log_classifier.predict(X3d_test_transformed)
    rocket_accuracies.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_sgd_pred))
    
    y_sgd_pred_training = sgd_log_classifier.predict(X3d_train_transformed)
    rocket_accuracies_on_training.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_sgd_pred_training))
    
    cv_accuracies = np.average(cross_val_score(sgd_log_classifier, X3d_train_transformed, y_train, cv= 5, verbose= 0,  n_jobs = -1))
    rocket_cv_scores.append(cv_accuracies)

# Adding text inside bars
def add_bar_text(bars):
    for bar in bars:
        plt.text(
            bar.get_width() - 0.01,  
            bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2,  
            str(round(bar.get_width(),2)),  
            va='center', 
            ha='right',  
            color='white',
            fontsize=8
        )

add_bar_text(bar_chart1)
add_bar_text(bar_chart2)
add_bar_text(bar_chart3)

Task 3¶

Evaluate alternatives to see if you can improve the accuracy on the raw data (Task 1). For this, you should consider alternative classifiers and data normalisation. The data should not be transformed beyond normalisation.

3.1 Data Normalization¶

In terms of normalizations, we have a few options. We could use MinMaxScaler normalization, which creates a range [0,1] using the minimum and maximum values or we can use RobustScaler, which uses the median and IQR, similar to StandardScaler, which we will also use.

We see that controlling for test and training data, RobustScaler gives the best accuracy score of 0.87. Second best is the MinMaxScaler with 0.80. StandardScaler performed the worst with an accuracy score of 0.71, which is surprising, since it is quite similar to the RobustScaler. In the grid search below, I will add the scaler as a grid item, so we can double check if the above results are consistent with the grid search.

3.2 Grid Search to find optimal model and parameters¶

I will check various classifiers and reasonable parameter options to see which model and parameters give he best accuracy score. I will also add the scaler option to double check which scaler gives us the best result as well.

In [32]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV, TimeSeriesSplit
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

In [33]:
#We can do a loop with a grid search to see the intermediate scores for the different classifiers, and also see 
#what the accuracy score is on the test set. 

classifiers = [
    (RandomForestClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__n_estimators': [10, 100, 1000], 
      'classifier__max_depth': [5, 10, 15], 
      'scaler': [StandardScaler(), RobustScaler(), MinMaxScaler()]}),
    (SVC(), 
     {'classifier__C': [1, 10, 100], 
      'classifier__kernel': ['linear', 'rbf'], 
      'scaler': [StandardScaler(), RobustScaler(), MinMaxScaler()]}),
    (DecisionTreeClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__max_depth': [5, 10, 15], 
      'scaler': [StandardScaler(), RobustScaler(), MinMaxScaler()]}),
    (KNeighborsClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__n_neighbors': [1, 5, 10, 20], 
      'scaler': [StandardScaler(), RobustScaler(), MinMaxScaler()]}),
    (SGDClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__alpha': [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01], 
      'classifier__penalty': ['l2', 'l1', 'elasticnet'], 
      'classifier__loss': ['hinge', 'log_loss', 'modified_huber'], 
      'scaler': [StandardScaler(), RobustScaler(), MinMaxScaler()]}),
    (GaussianNB(), 
     {'classifier__var_smoothing': [1e-9, 1e-8, 1e-7], 
      'scaler': [StandardScaler(), RobustScaler(), MinMaxScaler()]})
]

# To preserve the temporal order of the data, use TimeSeriesSplit for cross-validation
tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5)

# Loop over each classifier
for classifier, param_grid in classifiers:
    print(f"\nStarting Grid Search for {classifier.__class__.__name__}")

    # Create a pipeline with the current classifier
    pipeline = Pipeline([('scaler', StandardScaler()),('classifier', classifier)])

    # Set up GridSearchCV
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline,
                               param_grid=param_grid,
                               cv=tscv,
                               verbose=1,
                               scoring='accuracy')

    grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    print(f"Best accuracy score (cv) for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {grid_search.best_score_}")
    print(f"Best parameters for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {grid_search.best_params_}")
    
    best_parameters = grid_search.best_params_
    # Create a new pipeline with the best parameters
    best_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', best_parameters['scaler']),
        ('classifier', classifier.set_params(**{k.split('__')[1]: v for k, v in best_parameters.items() if k.startswith('classifier__')}))
    ])

    # Fit the best pipeline on the full training data
    best_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Evaluate on the test set
    test_predictions = best_pipeline.predict(X_test)
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, test_predictions)
    print(f"Best model accuracy on test set for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {test_accuracy}")

    # Evaluate on the training set
    train_predictions = best_pipeline.predict(X_train)
    train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, train_predictions)
    print(f"Best model accuracy on train set for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {train_accuracy}")

We have performed a grid search using various classifiers and performed 5-fold cross-validation. The best parameters were found to be the SVC classifier with C value of 100 and kernel= rbf with MinMaxScaler. Now that we have our ideal classifier, we can do further optimizations to improve the model accuracy.

At this point it is important to clarify what we are truly after. We want to find the model that has the highest accuracy rate on the test set as well as the cross-validation score, overfitting is not a major concern but we will test the model on the training set as a matter of interest.

I also want to note that SGDClassifier fitted a total of 405 models, and the process was quite fast.

Let us now increase the grid search granularity and see if we can further increase the accuracy score of our model.

Task 4¶

Evaluate alternatives to improve accuracy using the Rocket transformer. Test the Rocket transformer with different numbers of kernels. Consider alternative models for the classifier stage. Again, only the data for subject A should be considered. What conclusions can you draw?

4.1 Number of kernels¶

First, let's see how the number of kernels change the accuracy score on our previous Stochastic Gradient Descent Classifier. We know that the kernel is what dictates the size of the model feature space. This means, we control the model complexity, computational efficiency and overall generalization with this one parameter.

We could add the kernel number as a grid entry in a grid search, but we cannot visualize it in that case. So I will keep it separate in order to see it visually. Also, data transformation using Rocket is painfully slow.

In [35]:
def kernel_plotter(start, end, interval):
    acc_test = []
    acc_train = []

    for i in range(start, end, interval):    
        rocket = Rocket(num_kernels=i)
        rocket.fit(X3d_train)

        X3d_train_transformed = rocket.transform(X3d_train)
        X3d_test_transformed = rocket.transform(X3d_test)

        sgd_log_classifier = SGDClassifier(loss='log_loss', random_state=100)
        sgd_log_classifier.fit(X3d_train_transformed, y_train)

        y_sgd_pred = sgd_log_classifier.predict(X3d_test_transformed)
        acc_test.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_sgd_pred))

        y_sgd_pred_training = sgd_log_classifier.predict(X3d_train_transformed)
        acc_train.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_sgd_pred_training))   
    
    return acc_test, acc_train


acc_test, acc_train = kernel_plotter(1000, 20000, 1000)

#We can do a loop with a grid search to see the intermediate scores for the different classifiers, and also see 
#what the accuracy score is on the test set. 

classifiers = [
    (RandomForestClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__n_estimators': [10, 100, 1000], 
      'classifier__max_depth': [5, 10, 15]}),
    (SVC(), 
     {'classifier__C': [1, 10, 100], 
      'classifier__kernel': ['linear', 'rbf']}),
    (DecisionTreeClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__max_depth': [5, 10, 15]}),
    (KNeighborsClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__n_neighbors': [1, 5, 10, 20]}),
    (SGDClassifier(), 
     {'classifier__alpha': [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01], 
      'classifier__penalty': ['l2', 'l1', 'elasticnet'], 
      'classifier__loss': ['hinge', 'log_loss', 'modified_huber']}),
    (GaussianNB(), 
     {'classifier__var_smoothing': [1e-9, 1e-8, 1e-7]})
]

# To preserve the temporal order of the data, use TimeSeriesSplit for cross-validation
tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5)

# Loop over each classifier
for classifier, param_grid in classifiers:
    print(f"\nStarting Grid Search for {classifier.__class__.__name__}")

    # Create a pipeline with the current classifier
    pipeline = Pipeline([('classifier', classifier)])

    # Set up GridSearchCV
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline,
                               param_grid=param_grid,
                               cv=tscv,
                               verbose=1,
                               scoring='accuracy')

    grid_search.fit(X3d_train_transformed, y_train)
    
    print(f"Best accuracy score (cv) for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {grid_search.best_score_}")
    print(f"Best parameters for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {grid_search.best_params_}")
    
    best_parameters = grid_search.best_params_
    # Create a new pipeline with the best parameters
    best_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('classifier', classifier.set_params(**{k.split('__')[1]: v for k, v in best_parameters.items() if k.startswith('classifier__')}))
    ])

    # Fit the best pipeline on the full training data
    best_pipeline.fit(X3d_train_transformed, y_train)

    # Evaluate on the test set
    test_predictions = best_pipeline.predict(X3d_test_transformed)
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, test_predictions)
    print(f"Best model accuracy on test set for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {test_accuracy}")

    # Evaluate on the training set
    train_predictions = best_pipeline.predict(X3d_train_transformed)
    train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, train_predictions)
    print(f"Best model accuracy on train set for {classifier.__class__.__name__}: {train_accuracy}")

In [42]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


depth_range = range(1, 11)
estimators_range = range(10, 26)

accuracy_test = np.zeros((len(depth_range), len(estimators_range)))
accuracy_train = np.zeros_like(accuracy_test)


for i, max_depth in enumerate(depth_range):
    for j, n_estimators in enumerate(estimators_range):
        RFC = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=max_depth, n_estimators=n_estimators, random_state=100)
        RFC.fit(X3d_train_transformed, y_train)

        
        y_pred_test = RFC.predict(X3d_test_transformed) # Predict and calculate accuracy on test set
        accuracy_test[i, j] = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)

        
        y_pred_train = RFC.predict(X3d_train_transformed) # Predict and calculate accuracy on training set
        accuracy_train[i, j] = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)

accuracy_diff = accuracy_train - accuracy_test


# Function to plot heatmap
def plot_heatmap(data, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
    sns.heatmap(data, annot=True, cmap='viridis', xticklabels=estimators_range, yticklabels=depth_range)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

# Plotting accuracy heatmaps will help us determine the optimal parameters for our RFClassifier as we are 
# only varying 2 parameters.
plot_heatmap(accuracy_test, "RFC Accuracy on Test Set", "n_estimators", "max_depth")
plot_heatmap(accuracy_train, "RFC Accuracy on Training Set", "n_estimators", "max_depth")
plot_heatmap(accuracy_diff, "Difference in Accuracies", "n_estimators", "max_depth")

Utilizing a RandomForestClassifier within our specified parameter ranges, the highest accuracy achieved on the test set is 0.98 where the corresponding train set accuracy is 0.96.

So, to recap out efforts in this task:

  • RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=2, n_estimators=10)

Recall that the accuracies obtained in Task 2 was 0.92 for the test set and 0.94 for the training set when we used loss function log_loss for SDGClassifier. So, clearly we have managed to improve on this result substantially thanks to gridsearch and further parameter tuning.

To recap our finding thus far for this task, we have:

  • num_kernels = 10000
  • RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=2, n_estimators=10)
Conclusion:¶

Lowering the number of kernels did not lead to a better result in our case. The accuracy scores on the test set was only about 2% less than the accuracy scores of the training set. This seem to indicate that ROCKET does well at feature extraction and does not lead to too much overfitting. Compared to log_loss loss function for SGDClassifier in Task 2, we went from 92% accuracy on test set and 94% on training set to, 98% on test set and 96% on training set using RandomForestClassifier which is a noticeable improvement.
